<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Filing a Class Action Claim</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>How to find settlements you qualify for</h2>
  <p>You may automatically receive a notice by mail or email if you&rsquo;re a class member. You can also search settlement databases: TopClassActions.com, ClassAction.org, and PACER (federal court filings). Check your junk mail &mdash; many settlement notices are filtered as spam.</p>
  <h2>Completing the claim form</h2>
  <p>Read the claim form carefully. Many settlements require: proof of purchase, account numbers, last 4 digits of a credit card used, or a signed attestation. Submitting false information to claim a larger share is fraud. If you don&rsquo;t have documentation, many settlements accept sworn statements for smaller amounts.</p>
  <h2>Watch the deadline</h2>
  <p>Claims deadlines are strictly enforced. Late claims are typically rejected. Set a calendar reminder well before the deadline. Courts rarely grant extensions except for demonstrated excusable neglect.</p>
  <h2>Opt-out vs. participate</h2>
  <p>By participating (filing a claim or doing nothing), you release your individual claims against the defendant. If your individual damages are very large, consult an attorney about opting out and suing independently before the opt-out deadline.</p>
  <h2>Tracking your payment</h2>
  <p>After final approval and any appeals, the claims administrator mails checks or ACH payments. This typically takes 6&ndash;18 months after final approval. Check the settlement website for updates. Uncashed checks are cancelled after 60&ndash;180 days.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/class-action-misconceptions">common class action misconceptions</a> and <a href="/guides/how-class-action-settlements-work">how settlements work</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
